// apply pandoc div.sourceCode style to pre.sourceCode instead
(function() {
  var sheets = document.styleSheets;
  for (var i = 0; i < sheets.length; i++) {
    if (sheets[i].ownerNode.dataset["origin"] !== "pandoc") continue;
    try { var rules = sheets[i].cssRules; } catch (e) { continue; }
    var j = 0;
    while (j < rules.length) {
      var rule = rules[j];
      // check if there is a div.sourceCode rule
      if (rule.type !== rule.STYLE_RULE || rule.selectorText !== "div.sourceCode") {
        j++;
        continue;
      }
      var style = rule.style.cssText;
      // check if color or background-color is set
      if (rule.style.color === '' && rule.style.backgroundColor === '') {
        j++;
        continue;
      }
      // replace div.sourceCode by a pre.sourceCode rule
      sheets[i].deleteRule(j);
      sheets[i].insertRule('pre.sourceCode{' + style + '}', j);
    }
  }
})();
</script>

<h1 class="title toc-ignore">Getting Started</h1>



<p>Install phenoclone from GitHub.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb1"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb1-1"><a href="#cb1-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">library</span>(devtools)</span>
<span id="cb1-2"><a href="#cb1-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt; Loading required package: usethis</span></span>
<span id="cb1-3"><a href="#cb1-3" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#install_github(&quot;jason-nideffer/phenoclone&quot;)</span></span>
<span id="cb1-4"><a href="#cb1-4" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">library</span>(phenoclone)</span>
<span id="cb1-5"><a href="#cb1-5" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">library</span>(ggplot2)</span></code></pre></div>
<p>Loading in example seurat object <code>rna_tcr</code>. This seurat
object has already been annotated, so there is a column
(<code>CTaa</code>) in the metadata that specifies the TCR sequences of
the cell (which are used to identify clones). There are also columns
that specify what sample the cell is from (<code>sample</code>) and from
which patient the sample was derived (<code>cohortid</code>). Finally,
cells have been annotated according to their identity
(<code>cell_type</code>).</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb2"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb2-1"><a href="#cb2-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Load Data</span></span>
<span id="cb2-2"><a href="#cb2-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>rna_tcr <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">readRDS</span>(<span class="st">&#39;../Data/example_annotated_seurat.rds&#39;</span>)</span></code></pre></div>
<p>The first function that you should perform is called
<code>calculate_freq</code>, which will calculate the frequency of each
clonotype on a per-sample basis. It is recommended that you also provide
<code>cell_type</code> and <code>subject</code> column names so that the
algorithm can calculate the frequencies of different clonotype-cell_type
combinations and characterize clonotypes by their most frequent (mode)
cellular identity.</p>
<p>By default, <code>calculate_freq</code> will exclude cells without a
TCR from frequency calculations (<code>exclude_na</code> =
<code>TRUE</code>). You can opt to include NA values, and this will
decrease the frequency of all clonotypes, but this is not recommended
since it may make results less interpretable. Additionally, including NA
values may not be intuitive if your seurat object includes cells that
are not T cells.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb3"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb3-1"><a href="#cb3-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>rna_tcr <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">calculate_freq</span>(rna_tcr, </span>
<span id="cb3-2"><a href="#cb3-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>                          <span class="at">clonotype_column =</span> <span class="st">&quot;CTaa&quot;</span>, </span>
<span id="cb3-3"><a href="#cb3-3" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>                          <span class="at">sample_column =</span> <span class="st">&quot;sample&quot;</span>,</span>
<span id="cb3-4"><a href="#cb3-4" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>                          <span class="at">cell_type_column =</span> <span class="st">&quot;cell_type&quot;</span>,</span>
<span id="cb3-5"><a href="#cb3-5" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>                          <span class="at">subject_column =</span> <span class="st">&quot;cohortid&quot;</span>)</span></code></pre></div>
<p>After running <code>calculate_freq</code>, you will notice that new
columns have been added to the meta data of your seurat object.</p>
<ul>
<li><p><code>clonotype.identity_count_per_sample</code> describes the
number of cells with the same sample, clonotype, and cell type
information as the cell in that row.</p></li>
<li><p><code>clonotype_count_per_sample</code> describes the number of
cells with the same sample and clonotype information as the cell in that
row.</p></li>
<li><p><code>clonotype_freq_per_sample</code> is equal to
<code>clonotype_count_per_sample</code> divided by the number of cells
in the sample, excluding cells without a TCR (unless otherwise specified
via <code>exclude_na</code> = <code>FALSE</code>).</p></li>
<li><p><code>clonotype.identity_freq_per_sample</code> is equal to
<code>clonotype.identity_count_per_sample</code> divided by the number
of cells in the sample, excluding cells without a TCR (unless otherwise
specified via <code>exclude_na</code> = <code>FALSE</code>).</p></li>
<li><p><code>clonotype_identity_mode</code> is equal to the most
frequently observed ‘cell_type’ among cells with the same clonotype
information. This variable is calculated across all samples that come
from the same subject.</p></li>
</ul>

<p>By providing inputs for <code>sample.1</code> and
<code>sample.2</code>, you can calculate expansion between samples.
Clonotypes will be primarily sorted based on fold-change in frequency in
<code>sample.1</code> compared to <code>sample.2</code> and secondarily
sorted based on the difference in frequency between the samples.
<code>minimum_count</code> can be provided to exclude clonotypes with
low abundance across the included samples. (This can be relevant since a
clone may only be observed 1 time in <code>sample.1</code> and 0 times
in <code>sample.2</code>. This is technically “infinite” expansion by
fold-change, but you may have low confidence in this measurement or
doubt its biological significance and therefore want to exclude it.)</p>

<div id="visualizations" class="section level1">
<h1>Visualizations</h1>
<p>Before making plots, it is a good idea to run the
<code>plotting_aesthetics</code> function. This will allow you to
specify the order that you would like elements to be plotted in as well
as the corresponding colors. Specifying this information at the outset
makes it simple to make visually consistent plots across multiple
modalities.</p>

was chosen because it was determined (using the
<code>expanded_clones</code> function) to be the most expanded Th2 clone

that expand the most from sample ‘3354_T1’ to sample ‘3354_T2’. By
assessing the frequencies of these clonotypes across six longitudinally
collected samples from the same subject, we can observe what happens to
these clones after their initial expansion.</p>
